text: The champions begin their title defence at a ground where they have prospered under Pep Guardiola. Manchester City have scored 17 goals in their last four visits to the London Stadium and will start as heavy favourites against West Ham after beating Liverpool in the Community Shield. However the news that Leroy Sané requires knee surgery is a blow and West Ham have forwards who can hurt City, with Sébastien Haller and Pablo Fornals expected to make their debuts. Jacob Steinberg

Sheffield United return to the Premier League for the first time since the 2006-07 season. New signing Oli McBurnie is likely to start as a lone striker for Chris Wilder’s side. Bournemouth start the season with a long injury list but will be confident their new arrivals and experience can guide them to victory. Graham Searles

Given all the uncertainty of opening day games, Burnley at least provide some predictability. Deadline-day signing Danny Drinkwater is unlikely to play given his lack of action in the past year but returning local boy Jay Rodriguez should feature up front alongside Ashley Barnes. Elsewhere all will be as it was last season, in terms of personnel at least, though Sean Dyche will expect his team’s form to surpass 2018’s dismal start. For Saints Ralph Hasenhüttl could start new signings Che Adams and Moussa Djenepo, with £15m Adams expected to partner Danny Ings who made his move to St Mary’s permanent this summer. Paul MacInnes

All eyes on will be on Palace to see if Wilfried Zaha plays against the club he could have ended up joining this week, while Roy Hodgson must decided on a right-back following the departure of Aaron Wan-Bissaka. Everton head to Selhurst Park having drawn their last three visits, with Marco Silva to decided whether he will hand a debut to the Italy striker Moise Kean. Ed Aarons

Watford manager Javi Garcia is hopeful over the return of Gerard Deulofeu for the season opener at Vicarage Road after an injury absence last season. Doubt remains over whether Roberto Pereyra will start after a playing for Argentina in the Copa América. Brighton begin their challenge with a new captain, Lewis Dunk taking the armband from retired legend Bruno. Neal Maupay, Adam Webster, Leandro Trossard and Aaron Mooy may all make their debuts. Joti Birdi

Tottenham have a much stronger squad after their late transfer activity but how they will line up is not clear. Kyle Walker-Peters looks most likely to fill Kieran Trippier’s vacated right-back spot, though a retooled Moussa Sissoko in the role is not out of the question. Dele Alli is out with a hamstring injury. For big spenders Aston Villa the team could be anything, but a spine of Tom Heaton, Tyrone Mings, John McGinn and Wesley looks likely. Paul MacInnes

This is an early test of Wolves’ ability to cope with extra demands this season, as, just three days after a Europa League win in Armenia, they travel to one of the teams aiming to finish seventh or higher. Wolves should be match sharp, at least, so Leicester will have to get up to speed quickly – especially Caglar Soyuncu, the defender likely to be filling the gap left by Harry Maguire. Paul Doyle

A day of debuts and protests beckons on Tyneside where more than £100m worth of new attacking talent should be on view. While Arsenal fans hope to see Nicolas Pépé make his bow, their Newcastle counterparts are looking forward to Premier League debuts for Joelinton and Allan Saint-Maximin. “I’m going to have some fun and games with that one,” said Steve Bruce, referring to Saint-Maximin. Bruce’s first League game as Rafa Benítez’s successor threatens to be overshadowed by a proposed fans’ boycott as opposition to Mike Ashley’s stewardship of Newcastle mounts. A city centre protest march is also scheduled. Louise Taylor

Ole Gunnar Solskjær hopes his brave new world starts with a promising performance following a first summer in charge of Manchester United. Frank Lampard, in his competitive debut as the Chelsea No 1, will look for precisely the same from his team. Harry Maguire is set to make his bow for United, while Chelsea’s transfer embargo means no fresh faces were added in the window. Jamie Jackson

Unai Emery has somewhat of a selection headache for Saturday’s early kick-off. Academy graduates Reiss Nelson and Joe Willock impressed in the win at Newcastle but could make way for club-record signing Nicolas Pépé and Dani Ceballos, while David Luiz is in line for his debut. Sean Dyche believes his side have returned “clear-minded and with a more powerful edge”. He will be looking to build on their performance in the opening win over Southampton. Ed Henderson

Renewed optimism around Villa Park is reflected in record season ticket sales, and Dean Smith says his team’s ability to turn on the style at home will be key to them thriving this season. Eddie Howe reluctantly sold Tyrone Mings to Aston Villa during the summer and now his team must find a way past the centre-back if Bournemouth are to beat promoted opponents – something they failed to do last week against Sheffield United. Paul Doyle

Graham Potter will be reluctant to change a winning recipe after such a promising opening-day victory at Watford. Summer signings Neal Maupay, Adam Webster and Aaron Mooy may have to wait for their full debuts as Potter takes charge of his first competitive game in Sussex, while West Ham will be looking for a reaction after a humbling defeat to champions Manchester City. “I’m relishing it,” Potter said. “They are a tough side who’ll be looking to push on.” Ben Fisher

Abdoulaye Doucouré’s presence in the opposition midfield may prompt a wry smile from Marco Silva, given his problems in that department. Watford rejected two late offers from Everton for the 26-year-old this summer and, with Morgan Schneiderlin suspended and André Gomes doubtful, Jean-Philippe Gbamin is in line for his first start. The £22.5m signing endured a difficult introduction at Crystal Palace but Silva needs him and fellow summer recruit Moise Kean to get up to speed quickly. Andy Hunter

Steve Bruce is waiting on a fitness update from Allan Saint-Maximin, and expects Norwich to test a defence that struggled against Arsenal: “Their philosophy is ‘we’ll always score more than you’”. Daniel Farke has mounting injury concerns, with winger Onel Hernández damaging his knee after falling at home. Alex Tettey and loan recruit Ibrahim Amadou could be fit for a battle between two of the early relegation favourites. Niall McVeigh

Jürgen Klopp’s visitors face a quick turnaround after Wednesday’s Super Cup battle. Their hero in Istanbul, goalkeeper Adrián, is a doubt after hurting his ankle when a spectator ran on to the field during Liverpool’s celebrations. Naby Keïta remains unavailable, while Klopp’s first-choice front three played an average of 99 minutes in midweek. Ralph Hasenhüttl has a refreshed, injury-free squad and has urged Southampton to “be sharp and hunt” their opponents. They will have to be much better than in the second half at Burnley to upset the odds. Niall McVeigh

In only the second round of fixtures comes a contest that will offer an early season hint of these two teams’ prospects. Manchester City finished 27 points ahead of Tottenham last term so a draw would be an acceptable result for Mauricio’s Pochettino’s visitors. Pep Guardiola, though, will demand his team go for the jugular in what should, hopefully, prove a seismic, memorable encounter. Jamie Jackson

Sheffield United’s first home game in the Premier League for 12 years is bound to be an evocative occasion. While locals would like nothing better than to see local hero Billy Sharp score the winning goal, they will also be mindful of the threat posed by Palace’s Wilfried Zaha. Roy Hodgson concedes Zaha may leave south London before the European transfer window closes, but seems determined to start his side’s creative catalyst in South Yorkshire. Much may hinge on how Hodgson counters Chris Wilder’s famous overlapping centre-halves. Louise Taylor

Frank Lampard will have gleaned real positives from Istanbul, even if his first two competitive matches in charge of Chelsea have now technically yielded defeats to Manchester United and Liverpool. Leicester represent a different but distinctly awkward challenge on Sunday; this is the type of game the hosts will feel they must win in terms of a top-four pursuit but City won here last season and, even without Harry Maguire, Brendan Rodgers’ side boast pedigree and a considerable threat on the counter. They will be no pushovers. Dominic Fifield

Last week’s 4-0 defeat of Chelsea brought sunshine after a troubled summer for Manchester United. Ole Gunnar Solskjær has singled out Alexis Sánchez and Fred for encouragement though the Chilean and Brazilian appear unlikely to start against opposition United failed to beat in three meetings last season. Already five matches in, having reached the Europa League qualifying round, Nuno Espírito Santo made nine changes in Thursday’s 4-0 defeat of Armenia’s Pyunik, giving four new signings their first Wolves starts, with Pedro Neto marking his bow with a goal. John Brewin

Daniel Farke found himself in the odd situation of having to play down expectations before Chelsea’s visit to Carrow Road. “Listen, we spent less than £1m this summer,” he said, “Chelsea are the Europa League winners. We remain underdogs.” That the German has to issue such a reminder is a reflection on the quality of Norwich’s victory over Newcastle, but also the stuttering start of Frank Lampard’s side. There is more consternation for Lampard with the news that N’Golo Kanté is a doubt for the match, while Antonio Rüdiger remains unavailable. Norwich look set to name an unchanged side. Paul MacInnes

Southampton lost their opening two matches but tend to be tricky opposition for Brighton and will surely fancy their chances after Graham Potter’s attacking revolution stalled against West Ham. Kevin Danso could also debut to refresh Ralph Hassenhüttl’s defence – a unit that kept Liverpool in check for long periods last time out. The workout given to the backline should have them prepared to stifle Potter’s plans for keeping the good times rolling at the Amex. Graham Searles

After two matches the way Ole Gunnar Solskjær wants Manchester United to play is clear and he will hope this high-energy pressing game can break down Crystal Palace. Roy Hodgson’s side lost at Sheffield United in their last match and are seeking to bounce back yet this is an opponent Solskjær’s men will be disappointed not to beat at Old Trafford. Jamie Jackson

Sheffield United have enjoyed an impressive reintroduction to Premier League life but their manager, Chris Wilder, is rightly wary about the threat posed by Jamie Vardy. Like Wilder, Leicester’s star striker, is from Sheffield and began his career in non-league circles but there is one key difference; Vardy grew up supporting Wednesday. “I just hope a certain lad who supports the other firm down the road waits one more game before he scores his first goal of the season,” said Sheffield United’s manager. “We’ll have to be at our best to stop Jamie – and Leicester.” Louise Taylor

Pre-season has not had the cleansing effect Watford would have hoped. The blistering downward spiral of results from the end of last season has bled into this. Javi Gracia needs a spark and Ismaïla Sarr’s defence-shredding pace could be exactly that if he makes his debut. West Ham will hope Sébastian Haller is fit to return and able to capitalise on any fragility that two defeats and no goals has engendered at Vicarage Road. Add Watford missing Troy Deeney’s leadership and you start to feel slightly nervous for Gracia. Graham Searles

Both teams have made a 100% start to the new season but it will require a first win at Anfield for seven years, or a rare display of substance at least, for the visitors’ credentials to be taken seriously. Arsenal’s last three visits to Liverpool have produced 5-1, 4-0 and 3-1 defeats. There was another 5-1 humiliation in 2014 after Arsène Wenger’s team started the day as Premier League leaders. Arsenal’s quality up front could test a Liverpool defence that has not quite recaptured last season’s form. Andy Hunter

Can Bournemouth stop Manchester City? Probably not. Eight defeats from eight meetings in the Premier League speaks for itself. How Pep Guardiola’s side respond to completely dominating Tottenham but failing to win is key. If profligacy is again the order of the day then Eddie Howe could spring a surprise. A rather large if, however, considering the embarrassment of talent at Guardiola’s disposal. Graham Searles

Two games in and Steve Bruce feels backed into a corner. It was always going to be tough to take over from Rafael Benítez but the manner Newcastle’s defeat at Norwich appeared to crystalise the supporters’ worst fears. Where Benítez’s team would be ferociously well drilled on the road, Bruce’s was picked apart. A result might be beyond Newcastle at Tottenham but signs of cohesion and attacking punch are urgently needed. David Hytner

So far Wolves have combined domestic and European duties very impressively. Their squad has shown enough depth – thanks partly to Adama Traoré’s terrific improvement – to suggest that Nuno Espírito Santo could make some alterations to the lineup that achieved an excellent win at Torino on Thursday and still be confident of securing a first Premier League win of the season. Burnley, however, will be troublesome visitors so this will be a serious test. Paul Doyle

Ole Gunnar Solskjær will be without Anthony Martial but has backed teenage forward Mason Greenwood to play a bigger role after Alexis Sánchez’s departure. Manchester United suffered memorable defeats at the Dell but are unbeaten at St Mary’s since 2003. Ralph Hasenhüttl is eager to end that run and build on impressive away wins over Brighton and Fulham but the hosts also have attacking absences, with Nathan Redmond and Moussa Djenepo both out. Southampton begin the weekend in the relegation zone but victory would lift them above United. Niall McVeigh

N’Golo Kanté’s continued absence with an ankle injury is a blow for Chelsea, who will also be without Pedro against Sheffield United. However Frank Lampard will be confident of earning his second win as the Chelsea manager. Mason Mount and Tammy Abraham are in goalscoring form and Chelsea will expect to have too much for Chris Wilder’s side, who will hope John Fleck passes a fitness test on a thigh injury. Jacob Steinberg

Crystal Palace have not been given long to bask in last weekend’s victory at Manchester United. Colchester brought them down to earth with a resounding bump in midweek and now, in the type of game they must dread, their ability to open up unfancied teams at home will be tested again. Aston Villa led and held out for some time at Spurs in their previous away match and, with Tyrone Mings leading their backline, will target this as a chance to build on that impressive win over Everton. Dominic Fifield

This is a match that Leicester need to win if they are to fulfil their high ambitions. They have begun the season well but not yet hit top gear. With Ben Chilwell available again after injury and Harvey Barnes pushing for a start after last week’s goalscoring introduction at Sheffield United, they have the potential to blow Bournemouth away even if Eddie Howe’s side carry a threat, too. Paul Doyle

Manchester City last lost a league game at home on 22 December and as this was also the previous time points have been dropped at the Etihad this is likely an insurmountable challenge for Brighton. In fact, this could be a day when Graham Potter’s side will have performed admirably not to finish in damage limitation mode. Jamie Jackson

Teams who end a season badly invariably tend to start the next campaign slowly too. Watford are a case in point, with zero points from three games, picking up where they left off last spring. It leaves Javi Gracia under even greater pressure than Newcastle’s Steve Bruce. Last Sunday’s win at Newcastle brightened Bruce’s horizon appreciably but he is well aware that anything but victory will see the storm clouds descending on Tyneside once again. Louise Taylor

This could be a high-scoring game. Both sides have been leaky at the back and clinical in attack so far, with Sébastien Haller scoring twice for West Ham last weekend and Teemu Pukki leading the league with five goals. It is unlikely to be dull at the London Stadium, though Norwich’s defence could be strengthened by the return of Christoph Zimmerman. West Ham will be without Michail Antonio through injury. Jacob Steinberg

Burnley’s solid start could have been even better but for the 97th-minute penalty that allowed Wolves to grab a draw at Molineux. Sean Dyche has tipped Liverpool for the title and he knows they will be a tough proposition after a week of rest. Burnley were in Carabao Cup action in midweek, even if Dyche made sure to change most of his team for the defeat by Sunderland. Until European football starts, Liverpool’s only interest is in keeping their noses in front of Manchester City and they will not be expecting to drop points at Turf Moor. Paul Wilson

Wolves have embraced their return to European football with six wins out of six and while that form has yet to translate into a Premier League victory they will be buoyed by achieving their goal of qualifying for the Europa League. Thursday’s win over Torino was the ninth game in 36 days for Nuno Espírito Santo’s side and Everton, with new signings Moise Kean and Alex Iwobi pressing for full home debuts, have the pace to capitalise on any fatigue in the visiting ranks. Andy Hunter

This is a measure for where Arsenal’s season is going but Tottenham may find inspiration in north London where they could not against Newcastle. Mesut Özil is available but it would be a surprise if he features in the starting lineup considering the likelihood of Unai Emery selecting Nicolas Pépé, Alexandre Lacazette and Pierre-Emerick Aubameyang in an attempt to overpower Spurs. Graham Searles

Victory at Tottenham on his last away trip enabled Steve Bruce to lift morale and give the sceptics a weekend off at Newcastle. But that was Tottenham. This is Liverpool, a team that has set a new club record of 13 successive league wins, has not lost at home for 42 league games and can establish a new unbeaten league run under Jürgen Klopp of 22 games on Saturday. Newcastle have not won a league game at Anfield since Rob Lee and Andy Cole scored in a 2-0 victory in April 1994. Sean Longstaff has joined a lengthy injury list after damaging an ankle in training this week. Andy Hunter

Graham Potter insisted there were green shoots in Brighton’s performance despite a comprehensive defeat to Manchester City last time out and they will want to back up such confidence with victory against Burnley. Leandro Trossard picked up a groin injury on international duty with Belgium, while Danny Drinkwater will be absent for the visitors following a nightclub altercation. “They are human beings and people do get in scrapes,” Sean Dyche said. “We have talked to him and the rest will remain private.” Ben Fisher

Ole Gunnar Solskjær is almost in crisis-management mode. His Manchester United team have not won since the opening day and as he continues to bemoan missed chances, the decision not to replace Romelu Lukaku becomes ever more odd. Leicester arrive with three more points – they have eight – so this is a real challenge for Solskjær and his side. Jamie Jackson

Sheffield United have made the best start of the three promoted sides and did well to draw 2-2 at Chelsea. Chris Wilder will surely fancy his players’ chances at home to a talented but inconsistent Southampton. It is early days, and luck as well as scientifically calibrated training schedules come into these things, but they are a fit squad. Should that continue, their survival chances will be enhanced appreciably. Louise Taylor

Tottenham laboured to score in their previous home games against Aston Villa and Newcastle while looking vulnerable on the counterattack and there is no doubt that Crystal Palace will present a similar challenge. Mauricio Pochettino has suggested that the season starts now for his team, with the European transfer window closed along with the attendant uncertainty, and he has to hope they can find greater energy and incision. Palace have not scored in the league at Spurs in six attempts. David Hytner

The 130th anniversary of Molineux will be celebrated at this match, with Wolves hoping to mark the occasion by claiming their first league win of the season. They had a happy knack of beating top sides here last season, including Chelsea, but to get three points this time they will have to defend better than they did at Everton in their last outing. Chelsea, who have been even less sturdy this season, must improve, too. There is likely to be goals in a game that is very much up for grabs. Paul Doyle

Pep Guardiola confirmed the news that Aymeric Laporte will be missing for up to six months for Manchester City, but otherwise posted a positive injury bulletin with the news that Gabriel Jesus, John Stones and Ilkay Gündogan are available for selection. Any hopes Norwich had of staunching the flow of City’s all-star attack already look fanciful after Daniel Farke – whose team have conceded 10 goals in four games – said he has 11 injured first-team players, including all four of his registered centre-halves. Paul MacInnes

Early optimism remains in full flow at Everton, who travel south with a sense that things are beginning to click. Marco Silva’s summer signings Alex Iwobi and Moise Kean impressed on their full debuts last time out and he has a wealth of attacking options that can damage a brittle Bournemouth defence. Eddie Howe is boosted by the return of midfielder Lewis Cook, who could feature following a cruciate knee injury. Ben Fisher

Quique Sánchez Flores is back at Watford and it is fair to say he knows the score. “We don’t have time,” the manager said, with a nod towards the helter-skelter nature of Premier League football but, also, perhaps the reality that the Watford hot-seat is hotter than most. Rock bottom after four games, Sánchez Flores will face Manchester City after this daunting clash with free-wheeling Arsenal. Things could get worse before they get better. David Hytner

Aston Villa’s sense of injustice over their defeat to Crystal Palace has been festering for a fortnight but the visit of Manuel Pellegrini’s side should give Dean Smith hope of securing a second win of the season. But West Ham have made a solid start since their 5-0 defeat against Manchester City on the opening weekend and remain unbeaten away from home this season. Ed Aarons

Honourable displays at Chelsea and Manchester United so far this season have yielded just one point for Leicester, who will see the visit of Tottenham as an opportunity to prove their top-six credentials by beating one of the usual occupants of those spots. Spurs have yet to win away this season and victory at the King Power would be the perfect way to respond to the disappointment of giving up a two-goal lead at Olympiakos in midweek. Paul Doyle

Only a short while ago many Burnley supporters might have had a home fixture against newly promoted Norwich down as a banker, though that was before Teemu Pukki announced himself to the Premier League and before last weekend’s wholly unexpected toppling of champions Manchester City. The three points gained from that victory mean Daniel Farke’s side currently sit a point above Sean Dyche’s team in the table, and if Norwich are going to continue to be so adventurous just about any outcome is possible at Turf Moor. Though without a win since the opening day of the season, Burnley are still averaging a point a match, usually a blueprint for survival if it can be kept up, and a draw against the Canaries would probably satisfy all concerned. Paul Wilson

Phil Jagielka is guaranteed a warm reception on his return to the club he served with distinction for 12 years but his former teammates will have to improve significantly on their last outing at Bournemouth to receive the same from the Goodison faithful. Everton have been strong at home and taken maximum points so far, in contrast to their dreadful away form, but Chris Wilder’s newly-promoted side have impressed on their travels this season. Sheffield United came away with a point from both Bournemouth and Chelsea and should pose a real test to Everton’s creative options. Andy Hunter

The paper covering Manchester City’s cracks was torn down by Norwich but without John Stones’s slack passing they are likely to improve defensively. A strong showing in Ukraine also aids the feeling that their shock defeat was a freak aberration. Watford produced an upset of their own against Arsenal and deserved a first victory of the season in the dying embers. Quique Sánchez Flores’s positive effect was clear in his first game back in the dugout but that may not last long with Pep Guardiola seeking atonement for the Carrow Road calamity. Graham Searles

Newcastle’s very own divine ponytail is set to make his second debut for the club. Given that Andy Carroll is still short of fitness following his long awaited recovery from ankle surgery that bow is likely to come from the bench but Steve Bruce still hopes the one time England centre forward’s very presence inside St James’ Park will “give the whole ground a lift”. It is early in the season for relegation six pointers but both Bruce and Brighton’s Graham Potter could definitely do with three. Louise Taylor

Wolves are well below the standard they set last season and their league form has now bled into their Europa League campaign. A home loss against Braga – their 12th game of the season – continued the disappointing slide from draws to successive defeats. A side boasting so much talent should be doing better. Crystal Palace should look past their capitulation against Spurs and focus on edging what could be a drab encounter. Graham Searles

West Ham will see this as a fine opportunity to establish themselves as genuine contenders to finish in the top six. They won this fixture last season and are unbeaten in five games in all competitions before hosting Manchester United, who beat Astana in the Europa League on Thursday. While West Ham have few injury concerns, United are without Luke Shaw, Paul Pogba and Anthony Martial. Daniel James is also a doubt for Ole Gunnar Solskjær’s side. Jacob Steinberg

Arsenal need a pick-me-up after failing to win their past three as Unai Emery’s brittle backline continue to display a technical prowess akin to David Dunn executing a rabona. Aston Villa could provide just that. In their last five meetings Arsenal have won five, scored 18 and conceded none. Dean Smith’s side are well drilled and boast two clean sheets from three matches since losing their first two back in the top flight. Graham Searles

Chelsea and Liverpool both lost their opening Champions League group games during the week but the latter appear to be in a better place before visiting Stamford Bridge. Jürgen Klopp’s side have a five-point lead at the top of the Premier League and will be hopeful of maintaining their 100% record, especially as Chelsea are likely to be without Mason Mount after the midfielder suffered an ankle injury against Valencia. Jacob Steinberg

One of those quirks of the fixture list dictates that, by Saturday afternoon, Sheffield United will have faced both Merseyside clubs within the space of a week. Unfortunately for Chris Wilder beating a formidably in-form Liverpool at Bramall Lane will almost certainly prove infinitely tougher than winning at Everton last week. United fans should not expect to see too many party pieces from Wilder’s side. Louise Taylor

A 3-1 win at Brighton in the Carabao Cup gave Dean Smith’s much-changed side a welcome boost, but now they need to channel that positive energy into a league win having dropped into the relegation zone. Burnley arrive at Villa Park fresh from beating Norwich but are without an away win since April, while Villa have only conceded two goals at home this season. This promises to be a tight battle. Tomas Hill

This is a meeting between teams determined to bounce back from humbling defeats to League One opposition in the Carabao Cup. Bournemouth came unstuck at Burton and West Ham at Oxford but both sides, who made a combined total of 19 changes on Wednesday, head into the weekend keen to retain their place in the top six. Arthur Masuaku returns from suspension for West Ham, while Bournemouth could welcome back captain Simon Francis, who made his first appearance of the season in midweek. Ben Fisher

Chelsea’s midweek thrashing of Grimsby in the Carabao Cup was their first home victory under Frank Lampard. Now they need a league victory at Stamford Bridge and Lampard will expect his team to see off Brighton & Hove Albion, who are winless since the opening day. Reece James and Callum Hudson-Odoi will be in the squad after impressing against Grimsby but Emerson Palmieri is out with a thigh injury. Jacob Steinberg

After the euphoria of beating Manchester City, defeat at Burnley felt like a reality check for Daniel Farke’s side. Both teams have won just two of their six games so far and have shown little consistency. Roy Hodgson’s team have yet to register a convincing performance at Selhurst Park, but they will fancy their chances against a Norwich side that have shipped 14 goals and have only scored once on the road this season. Tomas Hill

Mauricio Pochettino says Tottenham need time to get over the effects of a tumultuous summer; the many players who wanted away cannot wave a magic wand and refocus. But time is rarely a manager’s friend and, with only two wins from eight matches this season, it would not be difficult to predict the hysteria if Spurs were to slip again. Southampton’s problem remains scoring Premier League goals. Can the 4-0 Carabao Cup win at Portsmouth unlock something? David Hytner

Scoring a late equaliser at Crystal Palace last week will have helped to convince Wolves players that they can still finish high up the table despite their lowly position at present. Then again, Watford enjoyed a rousing fightback against Arsenal two weeks ago and then were annihilated 8-0 at Manchester City, so momentum may be overrated. What is certain is that both sides will see this as a prime opportunity to claim their first league win of the season. Paul Doyle

Marco Silva is feeling the weight of expectation at Everton and his best line of defence may just be the fact that he is not Sam Allardyce – and now comes the first tall order of an already flaky second season since taking over from a hugely unpopular predecessor. City have managed 14 goals in their last three league matches, one of them the hiccup at Norwich. Everton, five league goals this season and firmly wedded to a 4-2-3-1 system which also has its detractors, will hope they too can capitalise on City’s makeshift centre-back pairing. The home side’s formation will be the least of their fans’ worries. Mark Tallentire

Steve Bruce is likely to approach this match in the same way that Rafael Benítez used to do, since the Spaniard’s counterattacking method brought victories on Newcastle’s last two visits to the King Power Stadium. Ayoze Pérez scored the winning goal on both occasions but, following his transfer to Leicester this summer, this time he will be on the opposite side. This would be a fine time for him to open his account for his new club, who will likely dominate possession on Sunday. Paul Doyle

Ole Gunnar Solskjær will take any kind of win over Arsenal as he seeks to lift the mood at Manchester United. The manager has up to eight players missing and may have to start the 17-year-old Mason Greenwood at centre forward. Unai Emery’s side have won their last three games in all competitions and have only lost once, against Liverpool in August. Jamie Jackson

Two teams in troubling form meet in Saturday’s early kick-off. Brighton have not won in the league since the impressive opening-day win at Watford, picking up three draws and scoring two goals since. They might be more exciting to watch under Graham Potter, but need at least a point to ease creeping doubts. With Solly March back from injury they must be hoping Spurs’ torrid week will get even worse after the hammering at home to Bayern Munich. Stephanie Fincham

The 5-1 home defeat to Everton at Christmas last year was a pivotal result in Burnley’s season. Joe Hart was dropped and a 4-4-2 formation brought back, which brought an almost immediate improvement on the pitch and in the league table as the Clarets climbed out of trouble. Burnley have been much more like their normal feisty selves this season and must be hopeful of taking something here. Marco Silva’s side showed signs of improvement against Manchester City last week, but at no time in the present campaign have they looked capable of scoring five goals. Silva has André Gomes and Theo Walcott available again after injury. Paul Wilson

Only Liverpool (49) and Manchester City (41) have won more points than Leicester’s 31 since the arrival of Brendan Rodgers as manager and Jürgen Klopp has grounds for concern ahead of his predecessor’s visit. Leicester were the last team to deny Liverpool a Premier League win at Anfield, back in January, but it is the impact of Wednesday’s frenetic Champions League win over Salzburg that is the main issue for Klopp. The leaders are enjoying their best-ever winning run in the top flight, and a 17th consecutive league victory would feel significant even at this early stage in the title race, given the calibre of the opposition. Andy Hunter

Norwich’s injury malaise shows no signs of abating. The Canaries are down to their third choice goalkeeper, Michael McGovern, while Grant Hanley has succumbed to a groin injury and Sam Byram is struggling with an ankle injury. Jamal Lewis will feature in this battle between promoted sides wearing protection on a damaged elbow. For Aston Villa, hopes of a first league away win of the season, and the chance to climb above their hosts, have been bolstered by the news that both Matt Targett and Tyrone Mings should be fit to play. Paul MacInnes

Sheffield United might be inclined to quip that Watford were the future once, as Chris Wilder’s overperformers prepare to face Quique Sánchez Flores’s underperformers, a side who were so buoyantly overachieving this time last year. The Blades ran Liverpool mightily close last week and might be looking forward to the space a leaky Watford might offer them at Vicarage Road. This is certainly a fixture they will be looking to win, and will be boosted by the return up front of Billy Sharp from his three-game ban, though Wilder may opt for the same XI that impressed against Liverpool. Will Hughes, Roberto Pereyra and Andre Gray could be in contention to start for Watford, who could do with the bite of the still-injured Troy Deeney. Tom Davies

Unbeaten in six matches, West Ham are starting to dream of a top-four challenge. However Lukasz Fabianski is set to be out for three months with a thigh injury and West Ham could suffer without the goalkeeper’s consistency. Crystal Palace, a point behind Manuel Pellegrini’s side, will be keen to find out whether Roberto, Fabianski’s deputy, has the quality to be a regular starter in the Premier League. Palace have problems of their own, with Luka Milivojevic suspended in midfield and centre-back Mamadou Sakho unavailable. Jacob Steinberg

Arsenal are on a seven-game unbeaten run, including a 4-0 win at home in the Europa League, and now face Bournemouth, who they beat 5-1 at home in February. What could go wrong for Unai Emery? The Arsenal manager knows full well his side are rarely more vulnerable than when they are expected to win, and Eddie Howe’s side are also in decent form. They were 2-0 up at Watford and had to hang on for a 2-2 draw, while at home against Aston Villa they ended up a goal and a man down – but fought back to win. And whither Mesut Özil? Only Emery knows. Conrad Leach

Since the surprise defeat at Norwich, Manchester City have reeled off five straight wins in all competitions, mixing their usual quality with a doggedness that is also a calling card of Pep Guardiola’s double champions. Wolves arrive off the back of a Europa League win in Istanbul, hoping to hand City a first home league defeat since Crystal Palace won 3-2 at the Etihad last December. That was 10 months ago; the odds are hugely against. Jamie Jackson

Both of these sides have been dogged by inconsistency so far this season, but both managers will see Sunday’s meeting as a winnable game. Chelsea have lost just once in 12 trips to St Mary’s, but Frank Lampard’s transitional side are more defensively fragile than previous incarnations. Ralph Hasenhüttl may call on Che Adams again after the goalless striker was rested against Tottenham, but Moussa Djenepo remains sidelined. Lampard is unlikely to make wholesale changes from the side that won at Lille in midweek, although N’Golo Kanté is a doubt. Niall McVeigh

The days when Newcastle challenged Sir Alex Ferguson’s Manchester United at the top of the Premier League under Kevin Keegan and Sir Bobby Robson are long gone. If Manchester United’s decline has been less dramatic, it is currently causing considerable consternation west of the Pennines. Steve Bruce’s Newcastle are in an infinitely worse mess though and must try to atone for last Sunday’s 5-0 reverse at Leicester. Can one of Ferguson’s stalwart centre-halves turn the tide on his native Tyneside? Louise Taylor

Manuel Pellegrini savoured his first win as the West Ham manager at Goodison last season, a comprehensive 3-1 victory, and a repeat could have serious repercussions for Marco Silva as he looks to halt a run of four straight league defeats that have left Everton in the relegation zone. Silva described this game as a must-win in the aftermath of defeat at Burnley before the international break. Everton’s performances have been as weak and the rising pressure on their manager, coupled with a disgruntled home crowd, offers a potent mix tthe visitors could exploit. Andy Hunter

The 5-1 thumping of Norwich must have left Aston Villa fans cursing the international break, with Dean Smith’s side having clicked into gear after a slowish start. Brighton come to Villa Park having lost the Carabao Cup tie against them last month but boosted by the victory over Tottenham. If either side loses they will be looking over their shoulders. Ed Aarons

Norwich travel to Bournemouth looking to turn the tide after three successive defeats. Daniel Farke’s side are yet to win on the road this season and Teemu Pukki’s strike at Anfield on the opening day remains their only goal away from home. The Bournemouth pair Callum Wilson and Joshua King will be rubbing their hands at the prospect of taking on the division’s leakiest defence, while the full-back Adam Smith could return from a hamstring injury. “I watched their first game against Liverpool,” said Eddie Howe, the Bournemouth manager. “I thought they did really well. They were beaten but I admire any team that has a clear philosophy and sticks with it.” Ben Fisher

Chelsea will expect to continue their winning run when they face Newcastle. They have climbed into fifth place and Tammy Abraham is in hot goalscoring form. However, N’Golo Kanté is out after suffering a groin injury on international duty and Newcastle have already claimed a couple of big scalps, winning at Tottenham in August and beating Manchester United two weeks ago. Jacob Steinberg

It will be an emotional day at what is Leicester’s last home game before the first anniversary of the helicopter crash at the stadium that claimed the lives of five people, including the club’s chairman Vichai Srivaddhanaprabha. While paying their respect, Burnley will aim to frustrate Leicester, testing their creativity and patience. While trying to work openings, Leicester will also have to be wary of counterattacks, because Sean Dyche’s side have scored in every away gamethis season, losing only once in four on the road. Paul Doyle

Tottenham could not have handpicked the next fixture after the shock 3-0 defeat at Brighton any better than to have a visit from Watford. Having also been announced as the latest subject of an Amazon fly-on-the-wall documentary for next summer, the US broadcaster will be fully expectant of filming a more joyful episode than it has managed of late, with Spurs winning three in their last 11 games in all competitions. Quique Sánchez Flores has said he is calm despite the current predicament, Watford have four league goals to their name and a goal difference of minus 16. “We are probably at 30 or 35%. We need to improve in many things if we want to be more competitive,” he said. “We are working really hard during the week.” Giovani Lo Celso and Ryan Sessegnon are back in full training for Spurs, who will be without Hugo Loris until the new year. Mark Tallentire

The international break came just as Wolves seemed to have found form, with the superb victory at Manchester City being their second league win in a row after a poor start. The challenge for Nuno Espírito Santo’s side is to pick up where they left off. The Southampton manager, Ralph Hassenhüttl, on the other hand has spent the break trying to tighten up his team, who have lost their past three league games. Unfortunately for Southampton, the midfielder Moussa Djenepo, who has not played since scoring the winning goal at Sheffield United, is not fit enough to return to action. Paul Doyle

After picking up 14 points from eight matches, confidence is high at Selhurst Park but the arrival of Manchester City will be a different test entirely for Roy Hodgson’s side. Pep Guardiola’s side ended a two-match sequence without a win against Crystal Palace in April with a 3-1 away victory but will know they cannot afford to slip up again after defeats against Norwich and Wolves. Ed Aarons

After eight games Ole Gunnar Solskjær is in crisis-management mode as his plunging Manchester Unitedside have left him feeling the pressure. If results go the wrong way United could be in the relegation zone by Sunday evening with the manager’s job prospects looking grim. The flip side is that victory over the league leaders could be the springboard to turn fortunes around. Jamie Jackson

After being desperately unlucky to lose to Liverpool in their last home game, Sheffield United are quietly optimistic as Arsenal head to Bramall Lane on Monday. Only a rare mistake on the part of Dean Henderson, United’s goalkeeper, gifted the league leaders a 1-0 victory and George Baldock, Chris Wilder’s right wing-back, gained immense confidence. “It was a really assured showing from us. We went toe to toe with arguably one of the best teams in the world,” he said. “I love playing at Bramall Lane – the fans are different class. There’s such a connection with the manager and the captain and it feels like we all have one aim to achieve things together; it’s brilliant to play in that atmosphere.” Louise Taylor

Dean Smith has Aston Villa looking like they belong in the Premier League but a visit to the Etihad Stadium may prove a chastening experience. Manchester City will be hungry to cut the gap, for a day at least, to three points behind Liverpool. Smith believes his side can get a result. “We’re not taking on a superhuman team, although they look like it at times,” he said. “It’s a team that can make mistakes and when they make mistakes you’ve got to punish them.” Graham Searles

Everton head to Brighton after their timely win over West Ham and, Yerry Mina’s knee problem apart, are likely to keep the same side as they seek their first away win of the league season. “What we have been doing away is not good enough,” said Marco Silva, who dropped his maligned zonal-marking system in the win over the Hammers and faces a big week with a League Cup tie against his previous club, Watford, coming up on Tuesday. Brighton won this fixture 1-0 last season but will have to cope without Aaron Mooy after the midfielder was sent off in the first half of their defeat at Aston Villa. “We have to give that a 100 and whatever per cent,” said their manager, Graham Potter. “We know it is a tough game but we want to bounce back ourselves.” Mark Tallentire

Watford are still searching for a win and will be looking to build on a positive display, that ended in a draw, against Tottenham in order to break their duck. A difficult proposition, considering no Watford player has scored more than one goal. Troy Deeney has been sorely missed and Bournemouth will be glad the striker still needs time to recover from a knee injury. Eddie Howe’s side are looking to end a winless run of their own stretching to four matches in all competitions. Graham Searles

This will be the first league meeting between the sides since West Ham stayed up at Sheffield United’s expense in 2007. However Chris Wilder insists United have moved on from the bitter row over the deal that brought Carlos Tevez and Javier Mascherano to West Ham. Wilder’s side will be more concerned with building on Monday’s victory over Arsenal. West Ham, who have lost their past two games, will need to be focused. Jacob Steinberg

Chelsea are on a run of six successive wins in all competitions with their latest a battling 1-0 away at Ajax. The young side’s ingenuity will be tested by Sean Dyche’s approach as they look for a seventh to solidify their place in the top four. Unfortunately Burnley’s Danny Drinkwater will not be ready in time to face his former club and Ashley Barnes and Chris Wood are touch and go to be fit in time. Graham Searles

Steve Bruce calls it “a conundrum”. With Andy Carroll injured, once again, can Newcastle’s manager somehow accommodate the newly fit Dwight Gayle and Joelinton in the team’s preferred 3-4-3 formation? It may be a little unconventional but one possibility under consideration is to play Gayle through the middle and shift Joelinton to the left-sided role he occupied for Hoffenheim last season. But where might that leave Miguel Almirón, who is still waiting to score his first Newcastle goal. And can Bruce’s players capitalise on any fatigue in the Wolves ranks following their Thursday night Europa League exertions. Louise Taylor

Arsenal scraped a win in the Europa League thanks to Nicolas Pépé and fans will hope the forward can repeat the trick to build some form for Unai Emery’s stuttering side. Will Mesut Özil play? Probably not. Roy Hodgson will be glad if he doesn’t because Arsenal are not creating enough chances for Pierre-Emerick Aubameyang at present. Palace’s Wilfried Zaha has been quiet this season, the Emirates could be the stage he has been waiting for. Graham Searles

Mauricio Pochettino’s struggling side confirmed “they have not forgotten how to play football”, as Jürgen Klopp put it, when they demolished Red Star Belgrade in midweek but a reunion with Liverpool may reopen insecurities. Tottenham faced Liverpool three times last season and lost on each occasion, with no reminder needed of what happened in the Champions League final 148 days ago. Anfield will provide plenty, however. The leaders are unbeaten in 44 league games at home and Spurs have won only once in their last 25 league visits. Andy Hunter

Manchester United made it over the line against Partizan Belgrade and finally won away but their lack of goals is a pressing concern. In their last 19 matches they have scored more than once on one occasion. Norwich’s porous defence could provide an excellent chance to improve on that though. After scoring for fun early on Daniel Farke’s side are struggling too. One goal in four matches since beating Manchester City speaks for itself. Graham Searles

Manchester United are targeting a fourth consecutive win in all competitions after an encouraging upturn in results, with Ole Gunnar Solskjær stating the October international break reinvigorated his squad after a tricky start to the season. Marcus Rashford, who scored a sublime free-kick in midweek, is touch-and-go owing to injury, while the defenders Harry Maguire and Victor Lindelöf are also doubts. Bournemouth, who failed to register a single goal last month, could welcome back the midfielder Dan Gosling following a hip injury. Ben Fisher

Unai Emery’s team selection will be under scrutiny against Wolves. Will Mesut Özil start after showing his worth against Liverpool in the Carabao Cup? It feels like a no-brainer. Emery’s side have been crying out for his ability to create something from nothing to feed Pierre-Emerick Aubameyang and Alexandre Lacazette. One decision that has been made is that Granit Xhaka will play no part in proceedings. Nuno Espírito Santo will hope the drama in north London continues so his side can go for six unbeaten after a rocky start. Graham Searles

Liverpool head to Villa Park aiming to maintain their six-point cushion over Manchester City before the two sides meet at Anfield next Sunday. Liverpool’s last visit here ended in a 6-0 away win, but Jürgen Klopp cannot expect such a one-sided contest on Saturday afternoon; only Bournemouth have won at Villa Park so far. Naby Keïta faces a fitness test and Joël Matip is unavailable for the visitors, while Jack Grealish is likely to be in contention for Aston Villa after overcoming a knock. Niall McVeigh

Brighton have turned the Amex Stadium into something of a fortress this season, having lost just once at home in the league and Graham Potter is eager for his team to continue their good form with victory over Norwich. Aaron Mooy will return to the squad from suspension but Potter may not want to change a winning formula after victory over Everton last time out. Daniel Farke’s side have mustered just a single point on the road since promotion and they have lost four of their last five matches but the German is staying upbeat. “We are not so addicted to the table,” Farke said. “I want this attitude that we are addicted to winning games.” Ben Fisher

Southampton may not relish a second trip to the Etihad Stadium in five days while Manchester City will not be daunted by facing a team they beat 3-1 on Tuesday in the EFL Cup and who were defeated 9-0 in their last league outing. Pep Guardiola’s side remain six points behind Liverpool so will be focused on not allowing a slip-up against the south-coast club that would represent a major shock. Jamie Jackson

It is a measure of how tight mid-table is that although Sheffield United currently stand eighth, they are only one point ahead of 13th-placed Burnley. Under the expert leadership of two excellent English managers in Chris Wilder and Sean Dyche both teams are exceeding expectations. Wilder and Dyche have been close since the early 1990s and took a golf trip together in the summer but neither man will be wanting to do his friend a favour. An intriguing tactical duel beckons. Louise Taylor

Newcastle lie a point above the bottom three before visiting the London Stadium. Steve Bruce’s side are capable of defending well but they have struggled in front of goal and need to provide better service for Joelinton, who has only scored once since his £40m move from Hoffenheim. A more ambitious attacking approach is required if Newcastle are to inconvenience West Ham, who are winless since beating Manchester United on 22 September. Jacob Steinberg

Watford are winless after 10 league games, and in danger of losing touch in the relegation battle – so the visit of a Chelsea side who have won every away game since losing at Old Trafford on opening day is far from ideal. Frank Lampard has warned his team against complacency, and has a selection dilemma up front after Christian Pulisic’s hat-trick against Burnley. Antonio Rüdiger is unavailable, while the match also comes too soon for Ross Barkley and N’Golo Kanté. Quique Sánchez Flores has called on the home fans to make plenty of noise at Vicarage Road on Saturday. Watford’s 4-1 win in this fixture last season is a sign of what they are capable of doing to top-six sides that underestimate them. Niall McVeigh

Leicester’s difficult second album is Crystal Palace away after they embarrassed Southampton 9-0 at St Mary’s. The team will surely remain the same so Roy Hodgson will know exactly what to plan for but executing that plan is another story. Jamie Vardy in title-winning form will be close to impossible to deal with. Not to mention the task of breaking down Leicester’s defence – the league’s joint-most miserly defence with eight conceded in 10 games so far. Harry Maguire? Who? Graham Searles

The table does not lie after 10 matches and 16th versus 11th in the Premier League says everything about the underachievement of two teams harbouring far greater ambitions. Everton have won their last two games at Goodison Park in league and cup yet, having suffered another avoidable loss at Brighton last weekend, even if controversial, it feels Marco Silva remains only one bad home defeat away from a full-blown crisis. Tottenham suffered their fifth defeat of the campaign on Merseyside last Sunday but showed enough quality on the counterattack at Liverpool to encourage Mauricio Pochettino. Andy Hunter

Stamford Bridge has not been a fortress for Chelsea this season. They have won three of their nine home games in all competitions and they will miss the suspended Jorginho against Crystal Palace, who have picked up impressive results at West Ham, Manchester United and Arsenal. Mason Mount is also a doubt with an ankle injury. Jacob Steinberg

Burnley are on a slide again after losing three league games in a succession, and a major concern for Sean Dyche will be the nine goals conceded in the process. West Ham are usually accommodating visitors in these circumstances, their recent away form has been poor and Burnley won this fixture last season comfortably, though Manuel Pellegrini is under a certain amount of pressure at the moment and can ill afford to be overtaken in the table by today’s opponents. Paul Wilson

It was a 3-1 home defeat by Eddie Howe’s Bournemouth in March 2016 that marked the end of Steve McClaren’s Newcastle tenure, prefacing his replacement by Rafael Benítez. Now the man in charge is Steve Bruce who, despite years at assorted clubs, has never faced Bournemouth as a manager. Whatever the result, Bruce is highly unlikely to be dismissed but will nonetheless be happy when the impending international break is over. “I shouldn’t say it but a lot of managers think ‘I have to get past the international breaks’,” he said. “In October and November some of us think we’ve got past that hurdle of getting the sack.” Louise Taylor

Everton head to St Mary’s for the first of two games with teams below them and a win essential if they are to tackle a difficult December in anything like good heart. Marco Silva, who has been less than strident in making his team’s case against controversial VAR decisions in the last two games – two penalties denied against Spurs, a shocker awarded to Brighton – and arguably costing his team five points in what is becoming an increasingly difficult season, will have to reshape the midfield again, with André Gomes joining Jean-Philippe Gbamin on the long-term injury list. Ralph Hasenhüttl has his own problems, winless in the league at home and desperate to rebuild confidence after their 9-0 shellacking by Leicester, though he has Moussa Djenepo available to start for the first time in weeks. Mark Tallentire

On the back of a convincing Champions League win in midweek, Tottenham would normally view the visit of a promoted team as a home banker. Spurs might have beaten Red Star Belgrade on Wednesday but they have not won consecutive games since April, their league results have been poor and Sheffield United, unbeaten away from home this season, arrive as the form team. Would something for the Blades even count as a shock?. David Hytner

The contrast between these clubs goes way beyond a six-point gap in the table. Arsenal are close to disarray, with a woeful away record, a dispute over the captaincy and doubts about the future of Unai Emery. At Leicester, harmony reigns and Brendan Rodgers is bringing the best out of an exciting young team. Rodgers says it is far too early to talk about a top-four finish but a win would increase those prospects and pile pressure on Emery. Paul Doyle

Manchester United are again looking up following the league defeat last time out at Bournemouth after Europa League knockout qualification was secured on Thursday with two group games left. Brandon Williams could make his full debut at left-back as Ole Gunnar Solskjær’s team look for a repeat of last season’s win, though Brighton arrive with two more points than United. Jamie Jackson

The lineups will be nothing like when they met in the Carabao Cup, and Wolves hope the result will be different, too. Because losing to Aston Villa twice in a fortnight would be tough to digest, especially as Dean Smith’s team would leapfrog them in the table. Villa arrive in good form despite recent defeats by Manchester City and Liverpool. Wolves have drawn their last three league games 1-1 and the same again would be no surprise. Paul Doyle

This is the one. The best teams in the country renew a rivalry that defined last season’s title race and may do so again providing Pep Guardiola’s injury-hit Manchester City keep up with Liverpool. Another win for Jürgen Klopp, who has beaten a team led by Pep Guardiola more times than any other manager (eight wins out of 17 meetings), would represent a monumental step for Liverpool, although City ended their unbeaten start to last season. The visitors have won once in their last 28 league visits to Anfield. Andy Hunter

José Mourinho would love to begin his reign at Tottenham by heightening the pressure on Manuel Pellegrini. Mauricio Pochettino’s replacement has rarely seen eye-to-eye with his West Ham counterpart, whose side have slipped towards the bottom three during a run of seven games without a win in all competitions. Yet this is a hard one to call. West Ham raise their level in this fixture and Tottenham have not won away in the league since January, which is partly why they felt compelled to replace Pochettino with Mourinho this week. Jacob Steinberg

Unai Emery has his board’s public backing but that will surely wear exceedingly thin if Arsenal slip up against Southampton or, next weekend, Norwich. He may spring a surprise by recalling Granit Xhaka – a temptation given the thin midfield options at his disposal – but is more likely to use the bulk of the side that put in an improved performance at Leicester before the international break, perhaps reverting to a back four. A dominant showing is needed, for the first time this season really, against opponents who should be there for the taking. Nick Ames

Bournemouth, on the slide after only one win in their past six matches, host one of the division’s form sides in Wolves, who have beaten only once in their past 11 games. Bournemouth will be without Josh King, who sustained a hamstring injury on international duty with Norway, so Dominic Solanke is likely to partner Callum Wilson in attack. Wolves will give Adama Traoré a late fitness test after the forward dropped out of the Spain squad last week with a hamstring problem. Rich Flower

Brighton will be without their captain, Lewis Dunk, for the match against Leicester. The centre-back serves a one-match ban after receiving five yellow cards. Adam Webster, who should be fit after an ankle injury, could replace Dunk in the side and will be tasked with containing Jamie Vardy. Brighton’s manager, Graham Potter, described the Leicester striker as ‘a top centre-forward, who does not need too many chances to score’ but his side have won their last three home games and so should be full of confidence. His counterpart at Leicester, Brendan Rodgers, believes the recent international break will not interupt the form of his side – they have won five out of six in all competitions. “I think it is important when players come back from international duty to press the reset button again,” he said. Rich Flower

Liverpool head to Selhurst Park having gone clear and beyond in the title race but with injury concerns. Potentially missing both Mohamed Salah and Andy Robertson hurts both attack and defence, with Robertson contributing four assists so far this season while Salah has scored six goals. Palace have the seventh-best defence in the league, but their lack of firepower up top has seen them score only 10 goals, the second lowest tally. If Liverpool score first, they will expect to take home three points. Will Dickson

Marco Silva believes Everton have “reacted strongly” to recent adversity, notably André Gomes’s horrific injury against Tottenham and the VAR debacle at Brighton, and three wins in their last five games in all competitions does suggest an upturn. They must exploit the lack of confidence in the league’s bottom club and give the manager’s claim greater substance. Silva’s side face a testing run of fixtures against Leicester, Liverpool, Chelsea and Manchester United following the visit of Norwich, who are without a win in seven matches since defeating Manchester City in September. Andy Hunter

Watford finally claimed their first league win of the season to lift them off the foot of the table with a 2-0 victory at Norwich. They could make it two from two against a Burnley team who have not won away all season, though Watford are yet to take all three points at home. Burnley’s Chris Wood and Ashley Barnes have ten goals between them so Watford will have to keep them quiet to prevent a record 11th consecutive home game without a win. Will Dickson

Here is a match the champions really have to win. If Liverpool beat Crystal Palace earlier on Saturday Manchester City will be 12 points behind at kick-off and so three points becomes vital against Frank Lampard’s resurgent Chelsea who arrive at the Etihad Stadium a place above Pep Guardiola’s team. The manager has Ederson back following injury and, given his side’s luck with VAR, will hope the contest will be incident-free. Jamie Jackson

Chris Wilder does not want Manchester United’s visit to turn into the “Harry Maguire Show” as the club’s one-time centre-back returns to his first club. From Bramall Lane’s academy Maguire progressed to Hull, Leicester and England, ultimately becoming the world’s most expensive defender when he arrived at Old Trafford in the summer. Sheffield United’s manager said: “I usually say it’s just the next game but perhaps this one does have a little more to it. It’s Manchester United and one of our former players will be playing for them. But I don’t want it to be ‘the Harry Maguire Show’. I want it to be the Sheffield United Show. I want us to show how good we are.” Dean Henderson, the home goalkeeper on loan from Manchester United cannot play so Simon Moore will get a rare outing. “It’s a great opportunity for Simon,” said Wilder. “I’m sure he won’t let us down.” Louise Taylor

Despite the summer of turbulence on Tyneside, Newcastle find themselves in a respectable 13th place in the table and could potentially win their third game in a row on Steve Bruce’s first return to Villa Park since his dismissal last October. Villa on the other hand, have lost their last three, albeit two of those were to Manchester City and Liverpool. Jack Grealish should be a welcome return to Dean Smith’s side after a calf injury. Will Dickson

Joelinton, Miguel Almirón and Allan Saint-Maximin cost a collective £77m but have scored only one goal between them. Nevertheless Steve Bruce will keep faith with the front three as Newcastle look to reprise last season’s win at St James’ Park. “I would love them to score a goal but the threat they’ve caused at the top end of the pitch and what they contribute towards the team is the thing I look at,” Bruce said. “At times they’ve been terrific and, when they do start scoring, we’ll be fine.” City face a testing run as they aim to keep in touch with Liverpool and cannot afford to drop points. Louise Taylor

Burnley are showing much more consistency after an uneven startand have climbed to seventh, sitting proudly above Arsenal, Manchester United and Spurs with not even a hint of dissatisfaction with the manager. Crystal Palace have lost their past three games since drawing with Arsenal at the Emirates but have a couple of away wins under their belt , one against Manchester United in August. Paul Wilson

West Ham are three points above the teams in the bottom three before visiting Stamford Bridge and are unlikely to find Frank Lampard in a charitable mood. The Chelsea manager will want his team to show no mercy against his former side and another defeat could force West Ham to sack Manuel Pellegrini. Lampard, who played for Pellegrini at Manchester City, is without Tammy Abraham after the forward injured his hip against Valencia. Jacob Steinberg

Graham Potter could not have a more daunting assignment after signing a six-year contract with Brighton than a visit to the Premier League leaders. Liverpool are unbeaten in 46 league games at Anfield, winning 36, and will equal the club record of 31 league games without defeat set by Kenny Dalglish’s team in 1987-88 should they maintain their imperious form. Fabinho’s absence through injury is a blow for Jürgen Klopp but he is not short of alternatives in central midfield. Andy Hunter

José Mourinho’s two games in charge of Tottenham have been manic but fans will breathe a sigh of relief they are safely through to the knockout stages of the Champions League. Bournemouth will hope Mourinho’s defence continues to struggle as they attempt to end a disappointing losing streak since beating Manchester United. Eddie Howe has to do without Josh King, with Ryan Fraser also a doubt, and the scales feel tipped in Mourinho’s favour. Graham Searles

The bottom sides meet in Saturday’s late kick-off, with the Premier League’s leakiest defence welcoming its least potent attack. Both sides began the season with top-half aspirations but face a battle to avoid being cut adrift over the festive period. Watford’s Quique Sánchez Flores faces a defensive injury crisis, with Craig Dawson and Christian Kabasele ruled out this week. Southampton will hope Danny Ings can take advantage and score for a third straight game. Niall McVeigh

Everything about this match was chucked up in the air by events at London Colney on Friday morning. What had been cast as a possible upset now looks like a chance for Arsenal to restore confidence, with interim coach Freddie Ljungberg expected to go back to basics. Norwich meanwhile look finally to be over their injury crisis and will have restored confidence after an away win at Goodison, though Alex Tettey misses out in midfield for family reasons. Paul MacInnes

Nuno Espírito Santo and Chris Wilder are managers in demand and their teams are likely to continue showing why when they meet at Molineux with both sides just outside the top four. Wolves have been juggling European and domestic duties well, so may not suffer any after-effects from Thursday’s draw on a heavy pitch in Portugal. Sheffield United, unbeaten away this season, will give them a stringent test anyway, especially with John Egan and Dean Henderson back. Paul Doyle

It would not be surprising if the only reason Marco Silva is still Everton’s manager is because no one else would want to walk into the hellish run of fixtures on which he is about to embark. Winning at Leicester would certainly silence Silva’s critics for a while but it is hard to see how such a result could be achieved, with Leicester’s fluency, solidity and sharpness offering an almost perfect contrast to Everton. A sixth consecutive victoryfor Brendan Rodgers’ team is the safest bet, particularly in light of a mounting injury list for the visitors. Paul Doyle

Manchester United are stuttering again and while the Europa League defeat at Astana on Thursday was with a youthful side, Ole Gunnar Solskjær’s team have to regain momentum. They will hope to do so against a Villa side with the worst away record in the division and who have won at Old Trafford once in 35 years. Jamie Jackson

There will be a rare bond of unity between the Everton crowd and technical area on Saturday when Duncan Ferguson takes temporary charge against Chelsea following the dismissal of Marco Silva. For all the goodwill that will come Ferguson’s way, his promotion is not a cause for celebration but a symbol of Everton’s malfunction under the erratic ownership of Farhad Moshiri. A club that has spent over £450m on players since Moshiri’s arrival finds itself in the bottom three and led by a sixth different coach in under four years. Chelsea will relish the opportunity. Andy Hunter

It is still early doors but Liverpool look head and shoulders above the rest in the Premier League. They are unbeaten in 32 games – a club record – and can win with explosive attacking power or with defensive grit and determination. Bournemouth’s chances of even a point look grim considering their best player this season – Harry Wilson – is unavailable to face his parent club. Liverpool have won their last four meetings by an aggregate score of 14-0. Graham Searles

Tottenham were strangely passive in defeat at Manchester United on Wednesday – the first bump in the road for José Mourinho. It felt as though the players were preoccupied by what United might do, rather than how they might impose themselves. Had Mourinho’s pre-match instructions been too reactive? Spurs will need greater positivity against a Burnley team who have lost five out of seven but always make life difficult. David Hytner

Crystal Palace have banked six points without conceding after a brutal run of defeats against Liverpool, Chelsea and Manchester City. Roy Hodgson will be confident his side can maintain their run against managerless Watford who are back in a rut. Seven points from safety could quickly snowball into being completely cut adrift if they do not hire the right man soon. Wilfried Zaha finding form escalates the danger of a fourth consecutive defeat. Graham Searles

Manchester City need a victory to ensure Liverpool’s lead is kept to a minimum of 11 points. For Manchester United it is about winning a consecutive league game for the first time since March. Both, of course, want the three points because this is the 179th Manchester derby. Jamie Jackson

Leicester have had seven wins in a row and Brendan Rodgers is the recipient of an extended and improved contract until 2025 after never quite ruling himself out of the vacant Arsenal job until Friday. Demarai Gray comes back into contention for Sunday’s trip to Villa after missing the last two matches with flu and the manager hopes Ben Chilwell will make it after missing the midweek win over Watford with a hip injury. Villa are a point above the relegation zone after their midweek defeat at Chelsea but they have Anwar El Ghazi in contention after a knee injury. “They are on a fantastic run of form but there aren’t many teams who will come away from Villa Park and think they’ve had an easy game,” Dean Smith said. Mark Tallentire

Southampton arrive on Tyneside bolstered by the collection of seven points in their past three games but Newcastle are buoyed by their haul of four from two tricky looking fixtures against Manchester City and Sheffield United. By making the most of sometimes startlingly low possession, Steve Bruce is not only beginning to win a few initially flinty hearts and minds at St James’ Park but seems to be bringing the best out of Jonjo Shelvey as he attempts to make the 3-4-3 template he inherited from Rafael Benítez a little more attacking while retaining its defensive meanness. Louise Taylor

Norwich came up as champions by five points from Sheffield United last season and this fixture finished as a 2-2 draw with Billy Sharp twice equalising for the Blades, who have adjusted to life in the top flight rather better than their peers. “Sheffield United have been settled at the back and have been able to play with almost the same starting lineup each week,” said Daniel Farke, whose side’s revival came to an abrupt stop at Southampton in midweek to leave them rooted in the bottom three. “We now have a home game and if we carry on in the way we finished that game then we have every chance of a win. It is not like Southampton played us out of the park, we were just bullied [at set pieces].” United’s Lys Mousset, who was dropped to the bench for the surprising home defeat by Newcastle on Thursday, is likely to be recalled. “It’ll be tough,” said the manager, Chris Wilder. “They were the outstanding team in the Championship last season. I was delighted to get as close as we did to them.” Mark Tallentire

After the highs of Thursday’s excellent and merited win at the Emirates Brighton return home and face a Wolves side who took their unbeaten league run to 10 matches with Wednesday’s 2-0 defeat of West Ham and are starting to look like the team who so impressed everybody last season. Nuno Espírito Santo’s side have now played 28 games in all competitions though, which is 11 more than Brighton, and their manager gave them a rare day off on Thursday – he will be hoping the extra day’s rest pays dividends for his players on Sunday as they aim to consolidate fifth place in the table. Paul Chronnell

Arsenal are the only team in the league not to have won a match in their last six and are winless since 6 October. Put simply this is relegation form. The club must find a permanent replacement for Unai Emery – crucially not Freddie Ljungberg – quickly to turn things around. West Ham reverted to type after beating Chelsea but the spiralling atomic nightmare that is Arsenal should provide a chance for Manuel Pellegrini to rebound once again. Michail Antonio’s fitness, or lack thereof, could be crucial to their chances. Graham Searles

“The plan is to make it the best time of our life,” said Jürgen Klopp when outlining his aims for Liverpool over the next five years of his new contract. The plan already appears well under way. The European champions booked their place in the knockout stage of the Champions League in midweek and host bottom club Watford seeking a 25th win from their last 26 Premier League games. Nigel Pearson, Watford’s 13th manager this decade, may have wished for an easier start in charge of the visitors. Andy Hunter

Burnley are below Newcastle in the table after three consecutive defeats and although allowances perhaps ought to be made for having to play Manchester City and Tottenham in that sequence, the aggregate score of 11-1 must irk a side who used to pride themselves on a miserly defence, as must the haunting memory of Son Heung-min’s wonder goal last weekend. Sean Dyche will be aiming to put things right against Newcastle, while aware Steve Bruce’s impressive turnaround on Tyneside has produced only one defeat in the past seven games. Paul Wilson

Bournemouth are a point above the bottom three before their trip to Stamford Bridge. Eddie Howe’s side have lost their last five games and will be without Nathan Aké and Callum Wilson against Chelsea, who reached the last 16 of the Champions League this week. If there is a positive for Bournemouth, though, it is that Chelsea have lost three of their last four league games. Jacob Steinberg

As Leicester chase Liverpool and records, they have shown a relentlessness that makes one fear for Norwich, owners of the second-leakiest defence in the Premier League. Brendan Rodgers’ side are aiming for a ninth straight win – that would equal the club’s best run across all divisions – and Jamie Vardy is hoping to score in a ninth consecutive game, which would edge him close to the milestone of 100 top-flight goals. He goes into this game on 96 and counting. Paul Doyle

Sheffield United are the front-running promoted side this season and will be confident they can build another unbeaten run against an Aston Villa side teetering just above the relegation zone. They have Brighton and Watford up next. If Dean Smith’s side do lose again and Southampton draw or win then they will sink into the bottom three. Sticking with an almost unchanged side after promotion seems to have worked for Chris Wilder while Villa, who signed 10 players in the summer, have struggled. Lys Mousset – the critical addition in attack to Wilder’s side – will relish Tyrone Mings missing out. Graham Searles

Manuel Pellegrini is clinging on to his job at West Ham but defeat here, and a potential tumble into the bottom three, would surely signal the end. The manager has to get his forward line firing again, and could recall Sébastien Haller and Andriy Yarmolenko. Pellegrini could also use a performance from Felipe Anderson like the one that earned all three points at St Mary’s last December. Southampton’s own mercurial playmaker, Sofiane Boufal, is likely to be restricted to a cameo off the bench again, as he manages an ongoing toe injury. Niall McVeigh

Manchester United are aiming to win three consecutive league matches for the first time since mid-January while Duncan Ferguson hopes to claim a second win in a row as Everton caretaker manager. This is United’s last league outing before Wednesday’s one-year anniversary of Ole Gunnar Solskjær’s temporary appointment so there is extra incentive to claim victory. Jamie Jackson

Wolves and Tottenham omitted key players from their European assignments in midweek in order to preserve them for this clash, which is crucial to their chances of finishing in the European places again this season. With Diogo Jota having scored five goals in his last two matches and Raul Jiménez and Adama Traoré fresh after a week off, Wolves have the firepower to expose the defensive frailties that José Mourinho has yet to resolve. Paul Doyle

Freddie Ljungberg oversees his fifth game as Arsenal’s interim head coach and the scalp of Manchester City would present a compelling argument for him to be offered the role on a longer basis. He has a number of injury concerns though, with Granit Xhaka and Kieran Tierney among those missing out, and must hope Nicolas Pépé is fit to start after what may have been a breakthrough performance in Monday’s win at West Ham. City, bruised by their defeat in the Manchester derby, are vulnerable but Ljungberg may need Arsenal to hit a level they have barely reached this season. Nick Ames

Crystal Palace’s season was summed up nicely by their goalless draw with Watford in midweek. A third successive clean sheet but no end product of their own. Roy Hodgson’s side have the second-worst scoring record in the league and Brighton will look to take full advantage in the M23 derby. Palace are without four defenders and will need a fill-in at left back too. A win for Graham Potter’s side will draw them level with Palace in the table. Graham Searles

Mikel Arteta will get a good look at what he is dealing with when he watches Arsenal play his former team. That said Arteta had an excellent view when Manchester City pushed them aside so effortlessly it would have made Roger Federer jealous last week. Duncan Ferguson is again in charge of Everton and the fight he has instilled will likely cause Arsenal problems. A defensive crisis is always looming at the Emirates and with no fit left-backs and Sokratis Papastathopoulos suspended another defeat is on the cards. Graham Searles
